<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-110-148 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 982 958</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  July 4 1991 v17 n14 p15(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Plesman Publications Ltd. (Canada) 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Lotus hops on another platform with Mac 1-2-3. (also plansSeptember shipment of 1-2-3 for Windows) (Micro Report)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ward, David.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Lotus Development Canada Ltd announces the impending release oftwo key products designed to bolster its profile in the graphicaluser interface market.andP;  According to company representatives,Lotus 1-2-3 for Macintosh is now in beta testing and should beshipped by Sep 1991.andP;  The program adds database and analysisfunctions including 3-D worksheets and portable menu features tothe Macintosh system, and will provide full support for AppleComputer Inc's System 7 operating system.andP;  Lotus 1-2-3 forMacintosh will retail for $599, including network server and nodeeditions.andP;  Also available about the same time, Lotus 1-2-3 forWindows will allow users to customize icons within an application.andO;It will sell for $719, with a network server edition available for$1,079.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Lotus Development Canada Corp. (Product development).andO;Product:   Lotus 1-2-3 for Windows (Spreadsheet software) (Productdevelopment)Lotus 1-2-3 for Macintosh (Spreadsheet software) (Productdevelopment).andO;Topic:     SpreadsheetsProduct DevelopmentMarketing StrategyGraphical User Interface.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>ETOBICOKE, Ont.andP;  -- Lotus Development Canada Ltd. has announced thelong-awaited Windows and Mac versions of its 1-2-3 spreadsheet but users willhave to wait before they get their hands on either package.andM;At an international &quot;video conference&quot; held recently, Toronto-based Lotus waslinked via satellite to its Cambridge, Mass.-based parent to announce the newspreadsheet products and outline the company's vision for softwaredevelopment in the future.andM;The vision, according to Frank King, senior vice-president of Lotus' SoftwareBusiness Group, includes the continued exploitation of graphical userinterfaces (GUIs), application integration and new applications specificallydesigned for groups or network environments.andM;In the meantime, Lotus must first concentrate on catching up to thecompetition in the GUI markets.andM;Today, there are roughly 14 million 1-2-3 users worldwide -- a figure whichtranslates to about 800 per cent of the overall spreadsheet market accordingto Colin Wyatt, general manager for Lotus Canada.andM;While Lotus has a huge DOS following, it has been without a Mac spreadsheetsince the company stopped marketing Jazz several years ago.andM;In addition, Microsoft Canada Inc. of Mississauga, Ont., released its Windowsspreadsheet, Excel 3.0, back in January.andM;&quot;We're going to fight like hell to make up for lost time,&quot; said Jim Manzi,Lotus chairman and chief executive officer.andM;While Wyatt acknowledged Lotus may have lost some users to Excel in recentmonths, he was equally confident of the company's chances to retain marketshare with 1-2-3 for Windows.andP;  &quot;Customers these days are buying a suite ofproducts -- they're buying strategy,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;Yeah, it's painful to waitnine months, but it's like anything else.andP;  The strategic advances of doingthat and keeping one version of your core number-crunching technology isprobably worth the wait.&quot;andM;Scheduled to begin shipping in late summer, one of the major features of1-2-3 for Windows is the collection of &quot;SmartIcons,&quot; which allow users tocustomize and define icons for application short-cuts, formulas or stylepreferences within the application.andP;  Currently in beta testing, 1-2-3 forMacintosh is scheduled to make its debut at about the same time as theWindows spreadsheet.andM;Manzi said 1-2-3 for Macintosh brings several new analysis and databasecapabilities to the Macintosh, such as 3-D worksheets and remote databaseaccess.andP;  The spreadsheet also features &quot;tear-off&quot; menus, which can bepositioned anywhere on the desktop, and fully supports Apple's new System 7operating system.andM;&quot;The ultimate goal is to abolish product boundaries,&quot; Manzi said.andP;  To thisend, the product will read and write 1-2-3 and Excel 2.2 and 3.0 worksheetfiles.andP;  The spreadsheet also comes with a 1-2-3 Classic feature, giving usersthe option of accessing the familiar 1-2-3 menu by hitting the &quot;slash&quot; (/)key.andM;&quot;I've heard, as you have, that this product was coming for a long, longtime,&quot; said John Sculley, chairman and chief executive officer of AppleComputer Inc., of Cupertino, Calif.andP;  &quot;This is clearly an important productfor us.andP;  It brings us further into the mainstream for business computing .andP;  .andO;.  It's a product who's time has come.&quot;andM;Wyatt said the ability to influence the Mac market has become increasinglyimportant for Lotus since Apple announced the Macintosh Classic and slashedprices on existing systems.andM;Once released, Lotus 1-2-3 for Windows will carry a suggested retail price of$719.andP;  Network server and node editions are expected to ship in the thirdquarter of 1991 for a suggested retail price of $1,079 and $719 respectively.andM;Lotus 1-2-3 for Macintosh is expected to retail for $599, and will alsoinclude network server and node editions.andO;</TEXT></DOC>